INSERT INTO `holiday_cat` (`id`, `name`, `image`, `note`, `productcat_id`) VALUES
(1, 'Transportation', 'Transportation icon - Greentours Indochina.jpg', '<p><img alt=\"Cyclo in Hoi An Ancient Town, Vietnam\" height=\"640\" src=\"/image/images/Vietnam%20Transportation%20-%20Greentours%20Indochina.jpg\" width=\"960\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">Along with tourism development, transportation in Vietnam has been&nbsp;developed with a variety means of transportation, which makes it easier for tourists to travel to Vietnam from other countries as well as travel within Vietnam. Main types of transportation in Vietnam are airplanes, cars, buses, trains, motorbikes and bicycles, etc.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">For getting in Vietnam: most Asian countries and a few countries from Europe, Australia and North America have direct flights to and from Hanoi airport and Ho Chi Minh airport. Travelers can also take a transit flights to other countries like Hong Kong, Seoul, Tokyo, Bangkok and Singapore, etc before arriving Vietnam.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">For getting around Vietnam: Depending on your time, budget and traveling style, you can fly straight to the destination, take a train or bus between cities and provinces or get on a motorbike for your own adventure. Within cities, besides taxi and buses, cyclo will bring you interesting experience while exploring every corner of cities.</p>\r\n', 144),
(2, 'History', 'History Icon - Greentours Indochina.png', '<p><img alt=\"\" height=\"641\" src=\"/image/images/Greentours%20indochina%20-%20Laos%20history(1).jpg\" width=\"960\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Laos is a small country with extraordinary beautiful landscapes and peaceful lifestyle, which is also known as the Land of Million Elephants.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After a long time experiencing the ups and downs of history, finally on December 2, 1957, the Lao People&#39;s Democratic Republic was established and this day became the National Day of Laos.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Laos fascinates visitors with the temples adopting unique architectures, beautiful waterfalls, and the hospitable nature of the local people. Lao culture embraces in itself plenty of wonders, including the rich options of culinary that has charmed many travellers.</p>\r\n', 145),
(4, 'History', 'History Icon - Greentours Indochina.png', '<p><img alt=\"\" height=\"534\" src=\"/image/images/Greentours%20indochina%20-%20Vietnam%20history.jpg\" width=\"800\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Throughout its formation and development, Vietnam was known to undergo through a great deal of hardships and struggle to thrive for a better life. Thus, war has become an indispensable part of its thousand-year long history. Yet many years have passed by and now the country has gradually regaining its peaceful ambience, as well as uncovering even more of its pristine beauty.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now Vietnam is the home to countless historical attractions where thousands of relics and antiques are preserved. The culture of Vietnam is partly affected by China, India and other countries in Asia, intermixing perfectly with its own features.</p>\r\n', 144),
(5, 'Dos & Don\'ts', 'Don\'t & Do Icon - Greentours Indochina.JPG', '<p><img alt=\"\" height=\"450\" src=\"/image/images/Vietnam%20dos%20and%20donts%20Greentours%20Indochina.jpg\" width=\"600\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>+ Prepare <strong>seasonal clothes</strong>: The weather in Vietnam is generally hot and humid, but winter in the North is very cold, so you should dress accordingly depending on when you are visiting<br />\r\n+ Wear <strong>appropriate attire</strong> when visiting temples and shrines.<br />\r\n+ <strong>Take a bite </strong>at the stalls on the street at least once. That&#39;s where some <strong>good food</strong> can be found!<br />\r\n+ Ask for<strong> permission</strong> before taking pictures, especially in remote areas.<br />\r\n+ Stroll around the Old Quarter, hop on a train to other city, board a cruise along the river, ride a bike through the lushful rice field or go for a cyclo trip to enjoy the bustling city life. <strong>Do it however you like</strong>!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>- Do not <strong>give money directly</strong> to ethnic minorities, you should donate to local charities or give them a small gift instead.<br />\r\n- Do not take photos where you are <strong>not allowed</strong> and avoid taking any pictures <strong>concerning the military,</strong> you wouldn&#39;t like to be behind the bars.<br />\r\n- Do not act <strong>too affectionate</strong> in public. Holding hands and cuddling&nbsp;for a bit are okay, but anything more than that and you should get a room somewhere.</p>\r\n', 144),
(6, 'Shopping', 'Shopping Icon - Greentours Indochina.jpg', '<p><img alt=\"\" height=\"452\" src=\"/image/images/Greentours%20indochina%20-%20Vietnam%20Souvenirs.jpg\" width=\"680\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>You should consult your friends or tour guide before purchasing or try to learn several Vietnamese words to bargain such as &quot;How much is this?&quot; or &quot;It&#39;s too expensive&quot; in case you get a sky-high price. If you are not happy with the deal, you may want to refuse, but try to stay friendly with the sellers and offer them a smile.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There a many gifts engraved with Vietnamese characteristics and culture&nbsp;that you can choose from. It can be artistic works created from rice, wooden souvenirs, clothes and miniatures or local handicrafts made from natural materials such as sea shells and sand.</p>\r\n', 144),
(7, 'Dos & Don\'ts', 'Don\'t & Do Icon - Greentours Indochina.JPG', '<p><img alt=\"\" height=\"450\" src=\"/image/images/Vietnam%20dos%20and%20donts%20Greentours%20Indochina.jpg\" width=\"600\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>+ Learn to live slowly, be patient and smile more when visiting Laos.<br />\r\n+ Ask for permission before taking pictures, especially in remote areas.<br />\r\n+ Wear appropriate attire when in Laos. Laotians are very discreet in how to dress, especially women. Therefore, wandering around wearing revealing clothes is considered impolite and disrespectful.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>- Touching or patting the head of a Laotian (especially a man) is not only abstinent but also considered as an insult, which can even lead to a serious scuffle.<br />\r\n- Do not touch a monk or give them anything. The only exception is during the alms ceremony when you give food in the bowls of the monks.<br />\r\n- Laos is not the ideal country for backpackers. 260 million unexploded bombs from 1964-1973 remain undiscovered. It is really dangerous if you accidentally wander into deserted trails or bomb-scattered areas.<br />\r\n- Do not act too affectionate in public. Holding hands and cuddling for a bit are okay, but anything more than that and you should get a room somewhere.</p>\r\n', 145),
(8, 'Shopping', 'Shopping Icon - Greentours Indochina.jpg', '<p><img alt=\"\" height=\"652\" src=\"/image/images/Greentours%20indochina%20-%20Laos%20Souvenirs.jpg\" width=\"990\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The abundance and diversity of goods for shopping in Laos cannot come close to that in Thailand or China, but you will probably find some unique items that cannot be found in any other country in the world. You can buy souvenirs such as traditional skirts of Laotian, silk, handicrafts or silver. Some items such as antiques and jewelry might come from smuggling, so you should consider carefully before buying for you might get in trouble when leaving Laos.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Laotians are often very frank with words so they hate quarrelling out loud. So if you would like them to lower the price, don&#39;t bargain too much, the employee might even sell you at a loss because they don&#39;t want to lose their face.&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 145),
(9, 'Health & Safety', 'Health & Safety - Greentours Indochina.jpg', '<p><img alt=\"\" height=\"533\" src=\"/image/images/Health%20and%20Safety%20in%20Laos%20-%20Greentours%20Indochina.jpg\" width=\"800\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">Laos is a safe and peaceful country to travel.&nbsp;The people are friendly and helpful. Petty crime is quite infrequent in in tourist areas, however you should still pay attention in crowded places and keep an eye on your bags.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">Pharmacies are common across Laos with assistants who can speak some English. Hospitals and clinics in Laos are not quite high standard but well equipped for diagnosing, treating malaria and dengue fever and handling minor and injuries. Travelers are advised to buy international health insurance in case you need to move to Thailand for serious injuries treatment. We recommend that visitors check with their government, your doctor or travel clinic for the latest information on health risks in&nbsp;Laos before departure.</p>\r\n', 145),
(10, 'Transportation', 'Transportation icon - Greentours Indochina.jpg', '<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" height=\"550\" src=\"/image/images/Transportation%20In%20Laos%20-%20Greentours%20Indochina.jpg\" width=\"870\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">Getting around Laos may be more challenging and slower than in other countries in the region but transportation network has been gradually improved. Depend on the destination and travel style, you can choose the suitable vehicles. Below is some most popular transportations in Laos:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong>Flights</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">If you do not have time, airplane is the suitable option for you to travel between cities, but it is more costly than other type of transportation.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong>Boats</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">Traveling by boat is one of the most popular ways in Laos. Taking a cruising trip along the Mekong river is also an interesting experience for travelers. There are several boat services such as slow boat, speed boat, traditional boat, etc with different price for you to select.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Buses</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Buses are the main transportation to travel between popular destinations and cities and the price is reasonable.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Tuk Tuk</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tuk Tuk is a unique and popular in Laos due to its suitable price and convenience. Taking a tuk-tuk ride around the city is an interesting way to experience the city&lsquo;s sites and the local&rsquo;s life.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 145),
(11, 'Top landscapes', 'Landscape icon - Greentours Indochina.jpg', '<p><img alt=\"\" height=\"315\" src=\"/image/images/Laos%20Top%20Landscapes%20-%20Greentours%20Indochina.jpg\" width=\"850\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Vientiane</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Vientiane is the charming&nbsp;capital in Laos. The city does not own large modern buildings, entertainment areas or busy streets, but there are numerous old stupa and temples dating back hundreds of years. You can also admire of French inspired architecture buildings in the city.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Luang Prabang </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Luang Prabang was the capital of Laos until 1975. Through many ups and downs, Luang Prabang still retains its inherent peaceful and ancient beauty, cultural values with unique architectures representing different historical periods of this land. It is recognized as&nbsp;a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1995.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Phonsavan</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Phonsavan is home to Plain of Jars -&nbsp;a famous archaeological site. The Plain of Jars is a megalithic archaeological landscape which consists of thousands of stone jars scattered along the valley and central plains of Xieng Khuoang Plateau.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Vang Vieng</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Vang Vieng is known for the peaceful countryside stretching along the bank of Nam Song River. This small town lies amidst the immense green forests and mountains, protecting its own pristine nature and tranquility. This place also attracts tourist because of outdoor activities including kayaking and tubing, hiking and exploring caves.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Si Phan Don</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The&nbsp;Si Phan Don which literally means Four Thousand Islands still retains a wild charm like a painting. You can admire the unique features of each island being immersed in sky clouds, vast rivers and surrounding landscape.</p>\r\n', 145),
(12, 'Health & Safety', 'Health & Safety - Greentours Indochina.jpg', '<p><img alt=\"\" height=\"640\" src=\"/image/images/Health%20and%20Safety%20-%20Greentours%20Indochina(1).jpg\" width=\"960\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">In general, Vietnam is a safe destination to come. The country is ranked one of the safest countries in the world for all visitors and solo travelers. Though there might be petty crimes on small-scale, it should not big problem if you keep a close eye on your bags when travelling on public transport and streets.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">Regarding healthcare,&nbsp; you can easily find have good state-owned and private hospitals and clinics with speaking English staff in big cities such as Hanoi, Ho chi Minh city and Da Nang. Besides, a lot of small pharmacies are common in most of the cities and in the rural.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">In addition, Vietnam is tropical climate country so make sure you bring plenty of sunscreen and use it throughout the day and you should also wear small mask to avoid dust and air pollution.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">Before your departure to Vietnam, it is advisable that you should consult your doctor or local travel clinic for the latest information on health risks in&nbsp;Vietnam to get precautions if necessary.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">Emergency contact number: Police (113), Ambulance (115), Fire (114).</p>\r\n', 144),
(13, 'Top landscapes', 'Landscape icon - Greentours Indochina.jpg', '<p style=\"margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; text-align:justify\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"499\" src=\"/image/images/VN%20Top%20Landscapes%20-%20Greentours%20Indochina.jpg\" width=\"800\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Hanoi Capital</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">Hanoi is the cultural, social, political and economic&nbsp;center of Vietnam. The charming capital attracts visitors for the hundred-year-old architectures, numerous iconic historical sites, mouth-watering cuisine and friendly people.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong>Ha Long Bay</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">Halong Bay is a precious reward that nature mother gives Vietnam. The Bay is dotted with 1,600 limestone islands and islets rising up from emerald crystal waters and covers an area of over 1,500 sqkm. A overnight cruise trip along the bay with full of activities such as sightseeing from the sundeck, visiting caves or islands, kayaking and bamboo boating is a great way to admire and explore this stunning nature wonder of the world.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong>Sapa</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">Sapa is the home to numerous ethnic minorities in the remote Northwest of Vietnam. The area has appealed flock of travelers each year for its magnificent scenery, colorful terraced rice fields, stunning mountain peak&nbsp;as well as distinctive culture. Sapa becomes a hotspot for a fascinating trekking adventure and this is the best way to enjoy authentic Sapa and experience indigenous life and cultures of tribal groups.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong>Hue</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">Hue is an ancient citadel of Vietnam under Nguyen Dynasty. &nbsp;The city possesses a large number of relics that still retain their inherent forms from the distant past such as Imperial Citadel, Forbidden Purple, ancient royal tombs with unique and mysterious architectural features. Taking a cruise trip along the Perfume, enjoying rich and strong flavor Hue cuisine while listening to the Royal music is the best way to feel the imperial city.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong>Hoi An</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">Hoi An Ancient Town was once a bustling international trading port and now has been recognized by UNESCO as a world cultural heritage since 1999, preserving numerous architectural heritages dating back hundreds of years. This is ideal place for those who love classical style old architectural houses and antique furniture. In addition, Hoi An is well known as the heaven for shopping and street food, visitors can buy handicraft and souvenirs and enjoy delicious dishes at a reasonable price.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong>Dalat</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">Located in Vietnam&rsquo;s central highlands. Dalat is known as the City of Love and Internal Spring&rdquo; due to it cool and temperate climate year-round, beautiful waterfalls, lakes, pine trees, gorgeous flowers and lovely French architecture villas which makes you feel like in Europe. Just enjoying an authentic coffee cup and admiring the scenic landscapes of the city can touch every travelers&rsquo; heart.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong>Ho Chi Minh</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">Ho Chi Minh City also known as Sai Gon is one of the most popular tourism destinations in Vietnam because of its classic French architecture, cultural diversity, ornate temples and pagodas, skyscrapers, rooftop bars and excellent cuisine. You can experience a mixture of &nbsp;traditional, historic and modern attractions in this bustling city.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong>Mekong</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">Mekong Delta known as Rice Bowl of Vietnam possesses a complicated system of rivers and canals. Here you can get one in life time experience on a sampan on river and mingle with the bustling atmosphere at the floating market in the early morning, admire the unique architecture of old houses or stroll around the fruit orchards for some sweet and fresh tastes of local products.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong>Phu Quoc</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">Phu Quoc is a truly paradise for those who loves the beach. Travelers will not only have a chance to indulge in crystal turquoise water, relax&nbsp;at the pristine sandy beaches and palm but also take part in a lot of interesting activities such as sunbathing, swimming, scuba-diving, snorkeling and enjoying the sunset.</p>\r\n', 144),
(14, 'History', 'History Icon - Greentours Indochina.png', '<p><img alt=\"\" height=\"540\" src=\"/image/images/Greentours%20indochina%20-%20Cambodia%20history(1).jpg\" width=\"960\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cambodia is officially known as the Kingdom of Cambodia, located on the Indochina peninsula in Southeast Asia, bordering the Gulf of Thailand in the south, Thailand in the west, Laos in the north and Vietnam in the east.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cambodia has a unique culture that is strongly influenced by the Indian culture and Buddhism. In Cambodian history, religion has played a major role in cultural activities. Over nearly 2000 years, Cambodian people have developed a unique Khmer tradition with mixed beliefs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The century-old temples, pagodas, or walls dated back to the ancient Khmer are still preserved until today, and one of the most famous is the architectural complex of Angkor. While admiring these buildings, one cannot help but respect the extraordinary strength and skillfulness of ancient Khmer people. Cambodian architecture also has a great influence on the architecture of Thailand and the Cham people of Vietnam.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cambodia is the most homogeneous nation with more than 90% of the population being Khmer and speaking Khmer, the official language. The Khmer people are very sincere and patient to overcome any hardship. Most Cambodians do not like the bustling city and prefer a peaceful lifestyle. The remainder are Vietnamese, Chinese Cambodians, Cams and Montagnards living in the northern and northeastern mountainous area.&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 143),
(15, 'Transportation', 'Transportation icon - Greentours Indochina.jpg', '<p><img alt=\"\" height=\"408\" src=\"/image/images/Cambodia%20Transportation%20-%20Greentours%20Indochina.jpg\" width=\"680\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cambodia&lsquo;s tourism has developed rapidly in the recent year, so does the transportation. With wide variety of transport options, travelling in Cambodia is now easier. Below is the list of popular means of transportation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Plane</strong>: For a fast and comfortable commute between the major cities of Cambodia and between Cambodia and Asian countries like China, Vietnam, Laos, Cambodia, and Thailand, there is no better option than to fly.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Bus and minibus</strong> are private run, there are a lot of bus companies between Phnom Penh, Siem Reap. Bus is the cheapest and the most convenient way to get around Cambodia, connecting all major cities and towns</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Tuktuk </strong>is one of the most popular transport option which is widely used in cities and towns. You can hire them for your private use for the whole day.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Motodup </strong>is a small motorcycle taxi ideal for short trip in cities and towns. As with tuktuks, it&rsquo;s important to agree the fare beforehand.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Bicycle </strong>is also a great way to experience the country while riding along scenic flat coastline and the rice paddy fields. Bicycles are available for rent at many guesthouses and rental stores with a reasonable price.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Train</strong>: &nbsp;A train service from Phnom Penh to Sihanoukville has just opened by the Government. The trains are modern and can be an alternative to buses however they run less frequently.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Boat</strong>: For years, boat was the principal means of transport in Cambodia, but these days with the improvement of major roads, it&rsquo;s easier and quicker to travel by road. However, boats still run daily between Phnom Penh and Siem Reap, as well as Siem Reap and Battambang.</p>\r\n', 143),
(16, 'Health & Safety', 'Health & Safety - Greentours Indochina.jpg', '<p><img alt=\"\" height=\"684\" src=\"/image/images/Cambodia%20Health%20and%20Safety%20-%20Greentours%20Indochina.jpg\" width=\"1024\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">Cambodia is a safe country both in larger cities and rural countryside. Crime rate in general are very low. Pickpockets are reported to be the most common issue when visiting crowded marketplaces or shopping areas. Be careful and keep your possessions hidden under your clothes to avoid being stolen.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">Medical services are available in all towns at government run hospitals and private clinics.<br />\r\nNon-prescription drugs are available at pharmacies hotels, and shopping centers. International class hotels also have their individual in-house medical Doctor to service their guests. Before departure to Cambodia, it is advisable that you should consult your doctor or local travel clinic for the latest information on health risks in&nbsp;the country to get precautions if necessary.</p>\r\n', 143),
(17, 'Shopping', 'Shopping Icon - Greentours Indochina.jpg', '<p><img alt=\"\" height=\"466\" src=\"/image/images/Greentours%20indochina%20-%20Cambodia%20Souvenirs.jpg\" width=\"700\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The monetary unit in Cambodia is riel, but dollar is also widely used and accepted everywhere. Even the banking system here is operated mainly in dollars. Shops in Cambodia mainly accept cash rather than credit card so it would be best if you prepare some before going shopping.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Be careful of fake goods when buying new or used gems. Make sure the place you buy them from is reliable and recommended by acquaintances. You should try to bargain, usually to half or 1/3 of the offerred price, also Phnom Penh is usually cheaper than Siem Reap.</p>\r\n', 143),
(18, 'Dos & Don\'ts', 'Don\'t & Do Icon - Greentours Indochina.JPG', '<p><img alt=\"\" height=\"450\" src=\"/image/images/Vietnam%20dos%20and%20donts%20Greentours%20Indochina.jpg\" width=\"600\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>+ Cambodians greet each other by clasping their palms in the same way as praying then bowing slightly. This is especially important to show your respect for the monks and the elderly.<br />\r\n+ Ask for permission before taking pictures, especially in remote areas.<br />\r\n+ Wear appropriate and not too revealing attire. This is mandatory for when you are visiting temples and pagodas, and you should also leave your shoes outside.<br />\r\n+ Use your right hand instead of your left hand, especially when shaking hands with other people. This is because Cambodians think the left hand is dirty for it is believed to only be used in the toilet.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>- Touching or patting the head is not only abstinent but also considered as an insult, which can even lead to a serious scuffle.<br />\r\n- Do not stand too close to or touch a monk. This is a taboo, even if you are their relative. You should keep yourself at a reasonable distance, talk politely not intimately, whether inside the temple or on the street.<br />\r\n- Avoid talking about sensitive topics, such as sex, war, politics, genocide, Khmer Rouge or Pol Pot.<br />\r\n- Do not act too affectionate in public. Holding hands and cuddling for a bit are okay, but anything more than that and you should get a room somewhere.</p>\r\n', 143),
(19, 'Top landscapes', 'Landscape icon - Greentours Indochina.jpg', '<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><img alt=\"\" height=\"396\" src=\"/image/images/Cambodia%20Top%20Landscapes%20-%20Greentours%20Indochina.jpg\" width=\"800\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong>Phnom Penh</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">Phnom Penh the vibrant bustling capital of Cambodia was once considered the Pearl of Asia. The capital city is famous for classic Khmer-style buildings, French architecture and Buddhist temples, modern restaurants and cafes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong>Siem Reap </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">Siem Reap is the major tourist hub in Cambodia as it is the gateway to magnificent Angkor Wat and also the base for visiting the Tonl&eacute; Sap Lake floating villages.&nbsp; The city is also ideal place for kick back where you can enjoy Pub Street with dances and parties.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong>Angkor Complex </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">Angkor is the most well known landmark of Cambodia. It includes famous Temple of Angkor Wat - the largest religious monuments in the world, Angkor Thom, the Bayon Temple and various ancient temples. Watching sunrise or sunset on the top is must do thing here.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong>Battambang</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">Battambang is one of Cambodia&#39;s largest cities but less visited than other bustling towns in this country. Battambang city still retains the ancient French architecture and the old temples. Here you can emerge in tranquil and peaceful scenery and experience famous Bamboo Railway.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong>Kampong Cham</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">Kampong Cham is a laid-back province in Cambodia and a ideal destination to enjoy rustic atmosphere and tranquil charm. You will see remnants of French colonial rule, ancient Wats and meet hospitable and friendly local.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong>Kratie</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">Kratie is a small colonial-style town situated on the east bank of the mighty Mekong River. It is the most popular place in the country to see Irrawaddy dolphins and great destination for watching sunset.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong>Sihanoukville</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">Sihanoukville known as beach town is home to white sand beaches and pristine islands. The city is ideal place to unwind by the beach, enjoy the fresh atmosphere, taste delicious seafood and join in many activities such as swimming, snorkeling or scuba trip, etc.</p>\r\n', 143);

